  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Understanding Salary vs. Hourly Pay</h2>
    <p>Whether you're negotiating a new job offer, planning your budget, or considering transitioning from a salaried position to freelance work, understanding the conversion between an annual salary and an hourly wage is crucial.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>The 2,080 Hour Rule</h3>
        <p>A standard full-time job in the United States consists of 40 hours a week for 52 weeks a year. 40 × 52 = 2,080 total working hours. This is the baseline number used to convert salaries to hourly rates.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Unpaid Time Off</h3>
        <p>If your hourly job doesn't offer Paid Time Off (PTO), you might only work and get paid for 50 weeks a year (2,000 hours). Keep this in mind when comparing an hourly offer to a salaried one with benefits.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Overtime Potential</h3>
        <p>Hourly (non-exempt) employees are typically eligible for time-and-a-half overtime pay for hours worked over 40 in a week. Salaried (exempt) employees usually do not receive overtime, regardless of hours worked.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>How to Calculate Salary to Hourly</h2>
    <p>To find your hourly wage from a salary, you need to know how many hours you work in a year. The formula is:</p>
    <p style="background: var(--bg-primary); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; font-family: monospace; text-align: center; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);">Hourly Rate = Annual Salary ÷ (Hours per Week × Weeks per Year)</p>
    <p>For example, if you make $60,000 a year and work 40 hours a week for 52 weeks:<br>
    $60,000 ÷ (40 × 52) = $60,000 ÷ 2,080 = $28.85 per hour.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>How do I calculate my hourly rate from my salary?</h3>
      <p>To calculate your hourly rate from an annual salary, divide your yearly salary by the total number of hours you work in a year. For a standard 40-hour workweek, there are 2,080 working hours in a year (40 hours × 52 weeks). So, if you make $52,000 a year, your hourly rate is $52,000 / 2,080 = $25 per hour.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>How much is $50,000 a year hourly?</h3>
      <p>If you earn a $50,000 salary and work a standard 40-hour week for 52 weeks a year (2,080 hours total), your hourly rate is approximately $24.04 per hour.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>How many working hours are in a year?</h3>
      <p>In a standard 40-hour workweek over 52 weeks, there are 2,080 working hours in a year. This assumes you are paid for 52 weeks, which usually includes paid time off (PTO) and holidays. If you take 2 weeks of unpaid vacation, your working hours would be 2,000.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>How do I convert an hourly wage to an annual salary?</h3>
      <p>To convert an hourly wage to an annual salary, multiply your hourly rate by the number of hours you work per week, and then multiply that number by 52 (the number of weeks in a year). For example, $20 per hour × 40 hours/week × 52 weeks = $41,600 per year.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Does my salaried hourly rate include paid time off (PTO)?</h3>
      <p>Yes, when calculating an hourly rate from an annual salary assuming 52 working weeks, the calculation inherently includes paid time off and paid holidays, as you are still being compensated for those hours as part of your total annual salary package.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

