  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>The Math Behind the Conversion</h2>
    <p>Understanding exactly how your salary is converted to an hourly rate helps you make informed decisions when negotiating job offers or switching careers. The basic formula is straightforward, but the nuances of your specific employment contract can change the final numbers.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Standard Formula</h3>
        <p>The standard conversion formula is: <strong>Hourly Rate = Annual Salary / (Hours per Week × Weeks per Year)</strong>. For a full-time employee, this typically looks like: $50,000 / (40 × 52) = $24.04/hr.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Accounting for Holidays</h3>
        <p>Even though there are typically 10-12 federal holidays in the US, salaried employees are still paid for these days. Therefore, the standard 52-week calculation is still accurate for your base hourly rate.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Leap Years</h3>
        <p>In a leap year, there are 366 days instead of 365, which occasionally results in an extra payday depending on how your employer's payroll cycle aligns with the calendar year.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Comparing Salaried vs. Hourly Offers</h2>
    <p>When you receive two job offers—one salaried and one hourly—comparing them requires looking beyond the base numbers to understand the total compensation package.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Benefits and Perks</h3>
        <p>Salaried positions often include comprehensive benefits packages like health insurance, 401(k) matching, and paid time off. These benefits can add significant value (often 20-30%) to your base salary.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Flexibility and Control</h3>
        <p>Hourly positions, especially freelance or contract roles, may offer more flexibility over your schedule and the ability to earn overtime pay, but they often lack the stability and benefits of salaried roles.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Taxes and Deductions</h3>
        <p>Both salaried and hourly employees are subject to payroll taxes (Social Security, Medicare) and income taxes. However, independent contractors (1099) are responsible for both the employer and employee portions of payroll taxes.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>How to Use This Calculator</h2>
    <p>Our Salary to Hourly Calculator is designed to be intuitive and flexible, allowing you to project your earnings in various scenarios.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Step 1:</strong> Choose your conversion mode (Salary to Hourly or Hourly to Salary) using the toggle buttons at the top.</li>
      <li><strong>Step 2:</strong> Enter your primary income figure (either your annual salary or your hourly rate).</li>
      <li><strong>Step 3:</strong> Adjust the 'Hours per Week' and 'Working Weeks per Year' to match your specific schedule.</li>
      <li><strong>Step 4:</strong> Review your personalized pay breakdown and the visual chart to see your earnings on a daily, weekly, bi-weekly, and monthly basis.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>By experimenting with different inputs, you can quickly see how negotiating a small increase in your hourly rate or working slightly more hours each week impacts your total annual income.</p>
